RBC or erythrocyte cells contains a tetrameric blood protein, hemoglobin which has a 3D structure with 4 subunits comprising of 2α (α1, α
                        2
                     ) and 2β (β1, β2) chains having an average molecular weight of 17 kDa per subunit. During the proerythroblast stage of the RBC life cycle, the ribosomes synthesize Hb [9]. Hb is responsible for carrying oxygen from lungs to tissues and return CO2 from tissues to lungs. In an oxygen prone environment, Hb is bound to O2, which later leaves the Hb in an environment where there is insufficient oxygen. Detecting Hb in biological fluids is of great importance for the diagnosis of various diseases like anemia, thalassemia, heart disease, leukaemia [10–14]. Hb based biosensing work has been reported in interdisciplinary fields of basic and applied sciences using various nanomaterials like graphene oxide [15], carbon [16–18], gold [19–21], silver [22], and iron nanoparticles [23] and other such nanomaterials to assess the extent of diseases (Table S1). Plasmonic biosensors are an intelligent contrivance in targeting biomolecules owing to its high specificity and sensitivity. Electrochemical sensors though effective may be inconvenient due to the requirement of a large quantity of sample, tedious analytical processes and dependency on the condition of an electrode in comparison to optical based sensors which overcome most of these issues. Among these nanomaterials, Silver nanoparticle (AgNP) has an unusual affinity for Heme group of Hb. Mahato et al. explained the complex formed between AgNP and Heme group promotes a conformational change in the protein structure involving the unfolding of Hb, leading to a transition from α to β-sheet structure [24]. In this regard, an optical study of Ag2O interaction with Hb would be significant to understand the biological activity of Hb on the surface of the nanomaterial. Ag2O is a p-type semiconductor with a bandgap of 1.46 eV, resembles the same body-centered cubic crystal as Cu2O with a packing of oxygen atoms with silver atoms occupying one-half of tetrahedral sites [25]. Unlike AgNPs, which has been enormously used for biosensing, Ag2O nanoparticles have been widely used for photocatalysis [26–29], fuel cells [30], photovoltaic cells [31] and antibacterial studies [32–35] because of its structural properties. To tune the optical and electronic characteristics of nanomaterials, scientists often prefer to engineer the morphologies of these materials. Each morphology exhibits a unique architecture of ordered assembly. In this regard, cube shaped nanomaterials possess high efficiency and high density due to their coordination of atoms around the corners or edges [36]. Silver based nanocubes have high optical sensitivity due to strong plasmonic modes amongst other morphologies and hence is suitable for biosensing [37,38]. Ag2O based nanomaterials tend to form metallic Ag under photo irradiation. In the case of Ag2O nanocubes the exposed planes are extremely sensitive to photo irradiation and unstable if exposed long-term to water. So photon irradiation on Ag2O nanocubes under water can expedite the conversion of Ag2O to AgOH and then Ag [39,40]. This issue can be resolved if Ag2O nanomaterials are capped with other compounds to increase its stability. Conducting polymers like PANI, Polypyrrole (PPy), polythiophene can bind with nanomaterials to make it more stabilize and electron rich. Amongst these, PANI has been explored on various horizons due to its unique properties like biocompatibility, light weight, high surface area along with long term environmental stability and low cost [41]. Polymerization of aniline yields both oxidized and reduced forms of PANI [42]. The emeraldine salt form of PANI displays high conductivity in comparison to its two other forms (leucoemaraldine and pernigraniline) due to its extensive π conjugation in the polymer chains and hence has wide applications from batteries, catalysts to biosensors [43–45].
